ETYMOLOGY. — The specific epithet in apposition refers to traditional Vanuatu’s goblins that are evoked by the mask sculpturing recognisable on the propodeum of the species. The anterior transverse carinae of propodeum are widened laterally, and flanked posteriorly by perpendicular striations that give appearance of “eyes”, while posterior transverse carina evokes a “mouth” (Figs 1C; 2). According to local beliefs on the west coast of Santo, mweramwera are small creatures with a child-like appearance that live in clearings and move in groups. People can attract them by calling them with a secret language. Mweramwera steal things, confuse people in the forest, but also perform a variety of odd jobs, such as finishing the mat a woman fails to complete it or bringing back lost items (
Tzerikiantz 2006
).
